Chapter Four (Continued)

Kierse studied him again, this time slower. Graves wasnt twitchy, but he wasnt still either. There was a kind of tension about himnot fear, exactly, but something contained. Like a blade still sheathed but humming to be drawn.

And what exactly do you want me to steal? she asked.

Kierse raised an eyebrow. That sounds like something from a fairy tale.

He glanced over his shoulder. It is.

She waited, letting silence pull the truth from him. It worked. He turned fully to her, expression unreadable.

They say it was forged by the Fae. That it can ring even when there's no wind, no hand to touch it. And when it doesit doesnt chime. It summons.

Kierse laughed, a sharp sound. What, spirits? Demons?

Something older, Graves said quietly. Something forgotten.

She hated how that gave her chills.

So you want me to steal a cursed necklace that may or may not exist, protected by whatmagic traps and ancient riddles?

That about sums it up.

She sighed and leaned against the parapet, suddenly tired. Why not just pay a team of professionals?

I did. They vanished.

Of course they did.

Her eyes narrowed. And if I say no?

He shrugged, but it wasnt casual. Then I suppose I keep looking. But I dont think Ill find anyone else with your... particular talents. Not in time.

That part caught her. In time for what?

Again, that smile. That irritatingly slow, secretive smile. Lets just say the necklace rings whether you want it to or not. The question is who its ringing for.

Shall we keep going from here? Theres a rhythm between them nowlike sparring partners who havent yet drawn blood.
